  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dmainbody><A name=3DBackground></A>
      <H2>The Problem</H2>
      <P>Authors increasingly cite webpages and other digital objects on =
the=20
      Internet, which can "disappear" overnight. In one study published =
in the=20
      journal <I>Science</I>, 13% of Internet references in scholarly =
articles=20
      were inactive after only 27 months. Another problem is that cited =
webpages=20
      may change, so that readers see something different than what the =
citing=20
      author saw. The problem of unstable webcitations and the lack of =
routine=20
      digital preservation of cited digital objects has been referred to =
as an=20
      issue "calling for an immediate response" by publishers and =
authors [<A=20
      href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#ref1">1</A>].</P>
      <P>An increasing number of editors and publishers ask that =
authors, when=20
      they cite a webpage, make a local copy of the cited =
webpage/webmaterial,=20
      and archive the cited URL in a system like =
WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>, to enable=20
      readers permanent access to the cited material.</P><A =
name=3DWhat></A>
      <H2>What is WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>?</H2>
      <P>WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>, a member of the International =
Internet=20
      Preservation Consortium, is an on-demand archiving system for=20
      webreferences (cited webpages and websites, or other kinds of=20
      Internet-accessible digital objects), which can be used by =
authors,=20
      editors, and publishers of scholarly papers and books, to ensure =
that=20
      cited webmaterial will remain available to readers in the future. =
If cited=20
      webreferences in journal articles, books etc. are not archived, =
future=20
      readers may encounter a "404 File Not Found" error when clicking =
on a=20
      cited URL. <A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/archive.php">Try =
it!=20
      Archive a URL here. It's free and takes only 30 seconds.</A></P>
      <P>A <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#How_look">WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>-en=
hanced=20
      reference</A> is a reference which contains - in addition to the =
original=20
      live URL (which can and probably will disappear in the future, or =
its=20
      content may change) - a link to an archived copy of the material, =
exactly=20
      as the citing author saw it when he accessed the cited =
material.</P>
      <HR>

      <H3>Overview</H3>
      <P><A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#How_look">How does a=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>-enhanced reference look like?</A></P>
      <P><A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#How_author">How do I use =

      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as a <B>(citing) author</B> to archive =
webpages I want=20
      to cite?</A></P>
      <P><A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#How_reader">How can I =
use=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as a <B>reader</B>?</A></P>
      <P><A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#How_editor">How can I =
use=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as an <B>editor?</B></A></P>
      <P><A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#How_Partner">How can I =
use=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as a <B>library, internet archive, or =
digital=20
      preservation organization</B>?</A></P>
      <P><A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#How_Cited">How can I use =

      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as a <B>citable Web-author</B> (blogger, =
copyright=20
      holder of Webpages, etc), or for self-archiving?</A></P>
      <P><A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#How_Publisher">How can I =
use=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as a <B>publisher?</B></A></P>
      <P><A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#ref1">References</A></P>
      <HR>
      <A name=3DHow_look></A>
      <H2>How does a WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>-enhanced reference look =
like?</H2>
      <P>A WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>-enhanced reference contains the =
traditional=20
      elements of a reference (e.g. author and title of the cited =
webpage, if=20
      known), the cited URL, and a <I>WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> =
URL</I>.</P>
      <P>There are two basic formats of a WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> URL: =
The opaque=20
      and the transparent format - the former can be used to be =
<I>added</I> to=20
      a cited URL, the latter can be used to <I>replace</I> a cited URL. =
Both=20
      formats will be returned in response to an <A=20
      href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/archive">archiving request</A>, =
usually=20
      initiated by the citing author. </P>
      <P>The opaque URL is very short and handy, containing a short ID =
like=20
      5Kt3PxfFl (http://www.webcitation.org/5Kt3PxfFl). This format =
should=20
      <I>only</I> be used in a reference where the original URL is still =

      visible:</P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>Plunkett, John. "Sorrell accuses Murdoch of panic =
buying",=20
        The Guardian, October 27, 2005, URL: <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://media.guardian.co.uk/site/story/0,14173,1601858,00.html">h=
ttp://media.guardian.co.uk/site/story/0,14173,1601858,00.html</A>,=20
        Archived at <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/5Kt3PxfFl">http://www.webcitation.org/=
5Kt3PxfFl</A>=20
        on December 4th, 2006. </BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>Alternatively, the cited URL and the cited date can be part of =
a single=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> URL (the transparent format), making it =
obsolete to=20
      spell out the original URL. The drawback is that the =
WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>=20
      URL can become pretty long: </P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>Plunkett, John. "Sorrell accuses Murdoch of panic =
buying",=20
        The Guardian, October 27, 2005, archived URL: <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/query?url=3Dmedia.guardian.co.uk/site/=
story/0,14173,1601858,00.html&amp;date=3D2006-12-04">http://www.webcitati=
on.org/query?url=3Dmedia.guardian.co.uk/site/story/0,14173,1601858,00.htm=
l&amp;date=3D2006-12-04</A>=20
      </BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>These are just examples, the actual citation formats preferred =
by=20
      different editors may differ. Most style guides currently give =
little or=20
      no guidance on how to cite URLs and their archived version, but =
most=20
      editors will accept something along the lines of citing the =
original URL=20
      together with the archived URL in a submitted manuscript. It is =
possible=20
      to omit the archiving or "accessed on" date (which is recommended =
in most=20
      style guides when citing URLs), because WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> =
always tells=20
      the reader when the snapshot was taken and in the transparent =
format it=20
      becomes part of the URL.</P>
      <P>Another form of a WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> link contains the =
cited URL and=20
      the <A href=3D"http://www.doi.org/" target=3Ddoi>DOI (Digital =
Object=20
      Identifier)</A> of the citing document (refdoi):</P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>IMEX. <A=20
        =
href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/query.php?url=3Dhttp://imex.sourceforg=
e.net&amp;refdoi=3D10.1186/jbiol36">http://www.webcitation.org/query.php?=
url=3Dhttp://imex.sourceforge.net&amp;refdoi=3D10.1186/jbiol36</A></BLOCK=
QUOTE>
      <P>This format is used by publishers who have implemented=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> (e.g. Biomed Central) by sending us their =
citing=20
      manuscripts shortly before or at publication (which our software =
combs for=20
      URLs which have not been archived by the citing author). A=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> URL containing a refdoi implies that a =
snapshot of the=20
      cited URL was taken when the citing paper (identified by its DOI) =
was=20
      published, and the archiving date of the snapshot retrieved by=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> if the reader clicks on this link will be =
close to the=20
      publishing date of the article. The example above is from the =
citing paper=20
      with the DOI <A=20
      href=3D"http://dx.doi.org/10.1186/jbiol36">10.1186/jbiol36</A>, =
which cites=20
      the URL http://imex.sourceforge.net (see reference 45). </P>
      <P>A fourth way to retrieve a WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> snapshot is =
using a hash=20
      sum (a sort of a digital fingerprint of a document), however, =
citing a=20
      document by URL and date is currently much more common than using =
a=20
      hash.</P>
      <P>A fifth way is that WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> may have (on =
request of the=20
      cited author/publisher) assigned a DOI to an archived snapshot, so =
that=20
      the link has the format http://dx.doi.org/10.2196/webcite.xx" =
(where xxx=20
      is the hash key of the material in WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>). The =
DOI resolver=20
      at dx.doi.org (which is commonly also used to resolve cited =
journal and=20
      book references) would then resolve to a WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> =
page (or an=20
      intermediary page pointing to the same work in other archives, to =
other=20
      manifestations such as print or pdf, or - in the case of online =
preprints=20
      - to "final" publications). </P>
      <P>For further information see <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/doc/WebCiteBestPracticesGuide.pdf">Bes=
t=20
      Practices Guide</A>. </P><A name=3DHow_author></A>
      <H2>How do I use WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as a (citing) author to =
archive=20
      webpages I want to cite?</H2>
      <P>WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> is an entirely free service for =
authors who want to=20
      cite webmaterial, regardless of what publication they are writing =
for=20
      (even if they are not listed as <A=20
      href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/members">members</A>).</P>
      <P>The author of a citing manuscript can:</P>
      <UL>
        <LI>Either manually initiate the archiving of a single cited =
webpage (by=20
        using either the <A=20
        href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/bookmarklet">WebCite =
bookmarklet</A> or=20
        the <A =
href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/archive.php">archive</A> page)=20
        and manually insert a citation to the permanently archived =
webdocument=20
        on webcitation.org in his manuscript, or;=20
        <LI>Upload an entire citing manuscript to the WebCite server via =
the <A=20
        href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/comb.php">comb page</A>, =
which=20
        initiates the WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> tool to comb through the =
manuscript=20
        and to archive all cited non-journal URLs. The =
WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>=20
        software also replaces all URLs in the manuscript with a link to =
the=20
        permanently archived webdocument on webcitation.org. =
</LI></UL><A=20
      name=3DHow_reader></A>
      <H2>How can I use WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as a reader?</H2>
      <P>Simply click on the WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> link provided by =
publishers or=20
      citing authors in their <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/#How_look">WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>-en=
hanced=20
      references</A> to retrieve the archived document in case the =
original URL=20
      stopped working, or to see what the citing author saw when he =
cited the=20
      URL.</P>
      <P>Readers can also search the WebCite database to see how a given =
URL=20
      looked like on a given date - provided somebody has cited that URL =
on or=20
      near that date. The date search is "fuzzy", i.e. the date does not =
have to=20
      match exactly the archiving date - we always retrieve the closest =
copy and=20
      give a warning if the dates do not match. A drop-down list on top =
of the=20
      frame with different dates tells readers that snapshots were taken =
on=20
      these dates. Select any of these dates to retrieve the respective=20
      snapshot.</P><A name=3DHow_editor></A>
      <H2>How can I use WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as an editor?</H2>
      <P>If you are a journal or book editor, publisher, or copyeditor, =
the=20
      first thing you should do is to insert a note in your =
"Instructions for=20
      authors" (<A=20
      =
href=3D"http://www.jmir.org/cms/view/Instructions_for_Authors:Instruction=
s_for_Authors_of_JMIR#webcite">example</A>)=20
      asking your authors to use webcitation.org to permanently archive =
all=20
      cited webpages and websites, and to cite the archived copy in =
addition to=20
      the original link.</P>
      <P>Secondly, editors/copyeditors should initiate the archiving of =
cited=20
      webpages (see instructions above <A=20
      href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/index.php#How_author">"How to =
use=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as an author"</A>) and replace all =
webcitations in a=20
      manuscript with links to the archived copy, before the manuscript =
is=20
      published.</P>
      <P>Thirdly, please notify us that you are using =
WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> -- you=20
      will become a member of WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> (which is free) =
by filling in=20
      <A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/mailform">the =
form</A>.</P><A=20
      name=3DHow_Partner></A>
      <H2>How can I use WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as a library, internet =
archive, or=20
      digital preservation organization?</H2>
      <P>WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> works with digital preservation =
partners who are=20
      running dark mirrors. This ensures that archived content remains=20
      accessible for future generations, and even if the =
WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>=20
      server is down. If you are interested, please fill in <A=20
      href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/mailform">this form.</A>. =
Current digital=20
      preservation partners include the Internet Archive as well as =
several=20
      libraries, through which WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> archived =
material may be=20
      available.</P><A name=3DHow_Cited></A>
      <H2>How can I use WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as a citable Web-author =
(blogger,=20
      copyright holder of Webpages, etc), or for self-archiving?</H2>
      <P>Academic bloggers and authors of non-journal scholarly webpages =
who=20
      foresee the possibility to be cited in the scholarly literature =
(=E2=80=9Ccitable=20
      Web-author=E2=80=9C or subsequently called =E2=80=9Ccited =
author=E2=80=9D), but are concerned=20
      about the persistence and citability of their work can add a =
WebCite link=20
      to their work (if you have a =E2=80=9Cbutton farm=E2=80=9D linking =
to Digg etc =E2=80=93 just add=20
      the button below). If your content is dynamically changing, then =
you can=20
      publish a button which creates a new archived version whenever =
somebody=20
      cites the work:</P>
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P><A=20
        =
href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/archive?url=3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Foalibrarian=
.blogspot.com%2F2006%2F07%2Fopen-source-open-access-and-open.html&amp;tit=
le=3DOpen+Source%2C+Open+Access+-+And+Open+Search%3F&amp;author=3DGiustin=
i+Dean&amp;date=3D2006-07-13&amp;source=3DOA+Librarian&amp;subject=3Delec=
tronic+publishing%3B+open+access"><IMG=20
        src=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/webcite.gif" border=3D0>Cite =
this=20
        page!</A></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>This will ensure that the reader (=E2=80=9Cciting =
author=E2=80=9D) knows exactly how to=20
      cite the work, and makes sure that a snapshot of the cited work is =

      preserved in WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> and its digital preservation =

partners.</P>
      <P>If your online content is static, and you want readers to cite =
a=20
      specific version, you can <BOLD><A=20
      =
href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/archive">self-archive</A></BOLD> your =

      work. You may then publish a button and link to the snapshot in =
the=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> archive within your work, or when =
referring to it:=20
      <BLOCKQUOTE>
        <P><A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/5TeS43Ipq"><IMG=20
        src=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/webcite.gif" =
border=3D0></A>Cite as:=20
        Giustini D. Open Source, Open Access - And Open Search? URL:=20
        =
http://oalibrarian.blogspot.com/2006/07/open-source-open-access-and-open.=
html=20
        (accessed 26-Nov-2007). Self-Archived at =
WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> on=20
        26-Nov-2007 [<A=20
        =
href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/query?url=3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Foalibrarian.b=
logspot.com%2F2006%2F07%2Fopen-source-open-access-and-open.html&amp;date=3D=
2007-11-26">http://www.webcitation.org/query?url=3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Foalibrari=
an.blogspot.com%2F2006%2F07%2Fopen-source-open-access-and-open.html&amp;d=
ate=3D2007-11-26</A>]</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
      <P>Thus, WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> can be used by authors as a =
one-click=20
      self-archiving tool, to ensure that for example preprints, =
discussion=20
      papers, and other formally unpublished material remains citable =
and=20
      available. All they have to do is to publish a preprint online, =
and then=20
      to self-archive it <A=20
      href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/archive">here</A>.</P>
      <P>Note that all these buttons should not be used for journal =
articles,=20
      which are presumably already archived through other mechanisms =
(LOCKSS=20
      etc.)</P>
      <P>WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> premium members will also be able to =
search the=20
      archive, assign a DOI to their work archived in =
WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP>,=20
      specify whether ads can be displayed (they receive a proportion of =
the ads=20
      revenues) etc. If a DOI is assigned, citing authors/publishers can =
use a=20
      link to dx.doi.org, which enables doi.org to resolve the link to =
either=20
      WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> or another archive, e.g. the Internet =
Archive, if a=20
      archived copy with an identical hash is found. </P><A=20
      name=3DHow_Publisher></A>
      <H2>How can I use WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> as a publisher?</H2>
      <P>Contact us to participate in the WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> =
collaboration by=20
      filling in <A href=3D"http://www.webcitation.org/mailform">the =
form</A>.=20
      Participating publishers include publishers of scholarly journals =
like <A=20
      =
href=3D"http://blogs.openaccesscentral.com/blogs/bmcblog/entry/webcite_li=
nks_provide_access_to">BioMed=20
      Central</A> who use WebCite to preserve cited webmaterial.</P>
      <P>They do this by encouraging their editors to instruct their =
authors and=20
      copyeditors to cache all cited URLs "prospectively" before =
submission or=20
      during the copyediting process, respectively, and/or by submitting =

      manuscript XML files to WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> at the time of =
publication, so=20
      that WebCite<SUP>=C2=AE</SUP> can comb through the manuscript and =
archive cited=20
      webpages automatically. We can also analyze back-issues of your =
journal(s)=20
      and archive the cited documents "retrospectively".</P>
      <H3>Implementation examples at publishers</H3>
      <P><A=20
      =
href=3D"http://blogs.openaccesscentral.com/blogs/bmcblog/entry/webcite_li=
nks_provide_access_to">Biomed=20
      Central</A> uses a WebCite <IMG=20
      =
